tr.td:
This is a 78-year-old female with complaints of bilateral shoulder pain right greater than left. Pain started a few months ago. Pain is located anterior lateral aspect of the shoulder. Pain with reaching. No pain at night. Radiates to the elbow but not beyond. Has taken ibuprofen. No prior injury. Minimal complaints of neck pain.
Past Family History, Personal and Social history and Review of Systems were reviewed with the patient and included in the chart.
Patient is awake alert oriented Ã—3. Patient is in no respiratory distress. Patient is a well-developed well-nourished individual in no acute distress. Patient has normal mood and affect. The patient is
5 foot 1, 145 pounds. Patient has full cervical range of motion, no provocative maneuver, mild paraspinal muscle tenderness. She has tenderness anterior lateral acromion.. Mildly positive biceps signs. No instability. Full range of motion. Motor sensory pulses are intact and symmetric. AP, outlet, and axillary view right and left shoulders are ordered performed interpreted by me today as showing type II acromion. Possible early arthritic changes glenohumeral joint.
Assessment: Bilateral shoulder pain. Symptoms consistent with rotator cuff tendinitis.
Plan: Patient will take Mobic 15 mg 1/day. Topical treatments discussed. Icing. Home exercise program given. Patient would benefit from right shoulder injection today. Patient will follow-up on an as-needed basis.
